AGI -&nbsp;The French President, Emmanuel Macron> and the British Prime Minister, Keir Starmer>, proposed a one-month truce in Ukraine. The same Macron says in an interview with Figaro. Macron does not believe a ceasefire agreement signed by Americans and Russians, convinced that Vladimir Putin will seek first of all to humiliate Ukraine, in particular dismilitarize it, writes the newspaper. Alternatively, he and Starmer put on the table a "trace in the air, seas and energy infrastructure" that would last a month. "We know how to measure it. It must be considered that the front, today, is the equivalent of the Paris-Budapest line. "In the event of a ceasefire, it would be very difficult to verify the respect of the front," the French President said.
The plan on Ukraine> that the UK intends to drive was discussed with Donald Trump. The British Prime Minister Keir Starmer said so. >"I spoke with President Trump last night (Saturday, ndr) - said Starmer in the press conference followed at the London summit - I will not enter into the details of that conversation, but I would not do this step forward if I did not think that it could produce a positive result, ensuring that we proceed together - Ukraine, Europe, United Kingdom and the United States - towards a lasting peace >" said the British prime minister. &nbsp;
"At the London table we are all determined to act for a solid and lasting peace in Ukraine and to ensure our collective security," wrote on social media the French President, Emmanuel Macron. In an interview with the 'Foglio', Macron > said that "if we want to be credible as European in our long-term support for Ukraine, we must be able to provide solid security guarantees. We're trying to move things. And we need Italy, a strong Italy that acts side by side of France, Germany, in the concert of the great nations. That is why I invited the Italian Prime Minister, Giorgia Meloni, on 17 February. It is necessary that Italy be at our side, that it commits itself on this path, and that it does it from a great European country, in the wake of what Mario Draghi did. At this moment we must remain united." &nbsp;
The leaders will meet again soon because "it's time to act", said Starmer at the end of the meeting of the 15 European leaders, with EU, NATO, Turkey and Canada. "We agreed that leaders will meet again very soon to keep up with these actions and continue working to achieve this shared plan. Today we are at a crossroads of history," he added.&nbsp;
President Giorgia Meloni met Starmer at Downing Street. At the centre of the interview Ukraine, but also the issue of migration and that of the common defence.
<div </div
"We are all very committed to the goal we all want to achieve, that is, a just and lasting peace for Ukraine," said the President of the Council during the institutional greetings at Downing Street. "At this moment it is very important that we speak, that we coordinate. Thank you for calling the summit," Meloni said.

&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"I believe it is very important that we avoid the risk that the West divides and I believe that Italy and the United Kingdom can play an important role in building bridges on this point: for this I have proposed a meeting between the United States and European leaders, because if we split up we will all be weaker," added Meloni.
&nbsp;"I am very pleased that we build our partnership from month to month on different central points - he continued - I am sure that we can do even better on issues such as security, defense, energy and fight against irregular immigration and traffickers of human beings. We need new tools and new ideas to ensure the safety of our citizens."
<h2>Starmer at Meloni: "We have similar approaches"</h2>
"It is great that you are here at this crucial moment and it was fantastic a few months ago in Rome to celebrate the closeness of our nations and to talk about the common concerns we have. Today we will talk about economics, migrations, security: we address these issues with very similar approaches." So the British premier, Keir Starmer, in the institutional greetings with Premier Giorgia Meloni at Downing Street.&nbsp;
<h2> Italy-Gb: focus on Ukraine, migrants and Gcap</h2>
At the heart of the talks - it recalls a note of Palazzo Chigi - the conflict in Ukraine, reaffirming the common commitment to the search for a just and lasting peace and the importance of maintaining the Euroatlantic unity, also in view of the subsequent meeting of the leaders hosted by the United Kingdom in Lancaster House.
The meeting also allowed the two leaders to take stock of the exceptional state of relations that unite the two nations and discuss the many strands of the bilateral agenda.
Particular attention was paid to the contrast of irregular migration and the fight against human trafficking, but also to energy, investment promotion and defence cooperation. In this area, both reaffirmed their commitment to the implementation of the Global Combat Air Programme (GCAP), a highly strategic international collaboration program involving Italy, the United Kingdom and Japan, with the shared ambition to develop a sixth-generation fighter. &nbsp;
<h2>Melons to Zelensky: "Partner and Usa for Fair Peace and Security"</h2>
The President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, met in London, on the edge of the meeting of leaders hosted by the United Kingdom, the President of Ukraine, Volodymyr Zelensky.
&nbsp;
The meeting, always informs a note of Palazzo Chigi, "has allowed us to reaffirm Italy's support for Ukraine and its people and the commitment, together with European, Western and United States partners, to build a just and lasting peace, which assures a future of sovereignty, security and freedom to Ukraine". &nbsp;
<h2>Zelensky thanks Meloni, production meeting
"I had a productive meeting with the President of the Italian Council of Ministers Giorgia Meloni to develop a joint action plan to end the war with a just and lasting peace," writes on X Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky. "No one, apart from Putin, is interested in the continuation and rapid return of war."
"It is therefore important to maintain unity around Ukraine and strengthen our country's position in cooperation with our allies, the countries of Europe and the United States. Ukraine needs a peace supported by solid security. I am grateful to Italy for its continued support and collaboration in fostering a closer approach to peace in Ukraine."
<h2> European leaders with Zelensky</h2>
<div </div
the summit of about fifteen leaders of allied countries of Kiev opened in London this afternoon in the presence of Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky, two days after his fierce confrontation with US President Donald Trump.
European leaders are addressing "a unique moment for Europe's security", said British Prime Minister Keir Starmer at the opening of the summit, which includes French President Emmanuel Macron, President of the Giorgia Meloni Council, German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, President of the Ue Ursula von der Leyen Commission and NATO Secretary-General Mark Rutte.&nbsp;
